1. What is the purpose of style tags and style attributes?
Answer: Style Tag: The HTML <style> tag is used to embed CSS into the HTML document and define style information (CSS) for a document. 
        It can be placed within the <body> tag or within the <head> tag. 
        This tag is also commonly referred to as the <style> element.
        
        Style Attribute: The style attribute specifies an inline style for an element. It is used to apply the styling declarations to be applied to the element.
        
        Inline: An inline CSS is used to apply a unique style to a single HTML element. 
        An inline CSS uses the style attribute of an HTML element.
        
2. Why do we use  ~  and >  symbols in css selectors? div ~  p ; div > p
Answer: 
~ Sign:
It is general sibling combinator and similar to Adjacent sibling combinator. 
The difference is that the second selector does NOT have to immediately follow the first 
one means It will select all elements that is preceded by the former selector.

> Sign:
It will target elements which are DIRECT children of a particular element.

+ Sign:
It is Adjacent sibling combinator. It combines two sequences of simple selectors having 
the same parent and the second one must come IMMEDIATELY after the first.

Reference: https://techbrij.com/css-selector-adjacent-child-sibling
